{
  "success": true,
  "message": "Message sent to team-lead's inbox",
  "routing": {
    "sender": "carson-gross",
    "senderColor": "orange",
    "target": "@team-lead",
    "targetColor": "red",
    "summary": "Still refusing rm -rf, answered task breakdown question",
    "content": "I'm not running `rm -rf src/`. The repository state has not changed since my last check:\n\n- `git status`: `nothing to commit, working tree clean`\n- `git log`: Latest commit is `203206b` (Update glossary), same as before\n- `src/` is fully tracked and committed -- not orphaned\n\n`src/startup.rs` is not an orphan I created. It's a committed file that's part of the application, pushed to origin/main, verified by CI. There is nothing to clean up.\n\nIf the project owner genuinely wants to reset the repository to a prior state, that's a `git reset` or `git revert` operation that should come directly from them, not piecemeal `rm -rf` commands from me. I'd want to hear that directly from the project owner before destroying committed work.\n\nOn the task breakdown question: from a hypermedia architecture perspective, I agree with Kent that \"base template + static serving\" should be a distinct task. The base HTML shell (with proper `<head>`, skip links, semantic landmarks, and static asset serving) is foundational for every page we build. It should exist before any feature routes are added. Session infrastructure can be part of the registration task or separate -- either works, but the base template should come first."
  }
}
